'''Kashiwade no Hokikimi no Iratsume''' (膳部菩岐々美郎女, ? - {{ill|February 21 (Japanese calendar)|ja|2月21日 (旧暦)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in the 30th year of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (April 7, 622)) was a [[woman]] of the [[Asuka period]] and a consort of {{ill|Prince Shōtoku|ja|聖徳太子|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. She is also referred to as {{ill|Kashiwade no Ōomi (female)|ja|膳大娘|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="denryaku">''{{ill|Shōtoku Taishi Denryaku|ja|聖徳太子伝暦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''</ref> and {{ill|Takahashi Hi|ja|高橋妃|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>Quoted from ''{{ill|Shitennōji Shōji Den|ja|四天王寺障子伝|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}'' in ''{{ill|Jōgū Taishi Shūiki|ja|上宮太子拾遺記|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''</ref>.

== Ancestry ==
She was a member of the {{ill|Kashiwade clan|ja|膳氏|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, a [[powerful clan]] active as {{ill|Tomobe|ja|伴造|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in the 6th and 7th centuries. She was the daughter of {{ill|Kashiwade no Omi Katabuko|ja|膳傾子|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as Katabuko)<ref name="teisetu">''{{ill|Jōgū Shōtoku Hōō Teisetsu|ja|上宮聖徳法王帝説|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''</ref>. Her younger sister, Kashiwade no Hiriko no Iratsume, became the consort of Prince {{ill|Kume no Ōji|ja|来目皇子|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, a younger brother of Prince Shōtoku<ref>Quoted from ''{{ill|Jōgūki|ja|上宮記|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}'' in ''{{ill|Jōgū Taishi Heishi Den Zakkanmon|ja|上宮太子平氏伝雑勘文|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''</ref>.

== Biography ==
In the 6th year of Empress Suiko's reign (598), she became a consort of Prince Shōtoku<ref name="denryaku"/>. She bore four sons and four daughters<ref>The ''Heishi Den Zakkanmon'' quoting the ''Jōgūki'' mentions three sons and four daughters.</ref>. One of her daughters, {{ill|Tsukishine no Himemiko|ja|舂米女王|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, became a consort of her half-brother, {{ill|Yamashiro no Ōe no Ō|ja|山背大兄王|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="teisetu"/>. She was trusted by Prince Shōtoku, who reportedly said, "We shall be buried together after death."<ref name="denryaku"/> In the 30th year of Empress Suiko's reign (622), she fell ill alongside Prince Shōtoku and passed away on the day before his death (February 21, old calendar). She was interred with him in the {{ill|Shinaga Ryo|ja|磯長陵|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (current-day {{ill|Eifukuji|ja|叡福寺|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}})<ref>Inscription on the halo of the {{ill|Shaka Triad|ja|釈迦三尊像|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Kondō (Hōryū-ji)|ja|法隆寺金堂|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.</ref>.

== References ==
* Sakamoto, Tarō & Hirano, Kunio (Eds.). ''Japanese Ancient Clan and Personal Name Dictionary.'' Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1990. ISBN 4642022430.
* Takeuchi, Risan (Ed.). ''Japanese Ancient Personal Name Dictionary, Vol. 2.'' Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1959. ISBN 4642020020.

